# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: floorplanning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The **aspect ratio** of an image is the ratio of its width to its height.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is expressed as two numbers separated by a colon, in the format width:height.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Common aspect ratios are 1.85:1 and 2.39:1 in cinematography, 4:3 (originally) and 16:9 in television, and 3:2 in still photography.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Other common display aspect ratios include 5:4 and 16:10.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The 1:1 aspect ratio is used for square images, often seen on social media platforms like Instagram, and 21:9 is an "ultrawide" aspect ratio popular for gaming and desktop monitors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The common film aspect ratios used in theaters are 1.85:1 and 2.39:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Two common videographic aspect ratios are 4:3 (1.3:1), the universal video format of the 20th century, and 16:9 (1.7:1), universal for high-definition television and European digital television.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Other cinematic and video aspect ratios exist, but are used infrequently.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In still camera photography, the most common aspect ratios are 4:3, 3:2 (1.5:1), and more recently found in consumer cameras, 16:9.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Other aspect ratios, such as 5:3, 5:4, and 1:1 (square format), are used in photography as well, particularly in medium format and large format.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In motion picture formats, the physical size of the film area between the sprocket perforations determines the image's size.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The universal standard (established by William Dickson and Thomas Edison in 1892) is a frame that is four perforations high.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The film itself is 35 mm wide (1.38 in), but the area between the perforations is 24.89 mm × 18.67 mm (0.980 in × 0.735 in), leaving the de facto ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] With a space designated for the standard optical soundtrack, and the frame size reduced to maintain an image that is wider than tall; this resulted in the Academy aperture of 22 mm × 16 mm (0.866 in × 0.630 in) or 1.375:1 aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The motion picture industry convention assigns a value of 1 to the image's height; an anamorphic frame (since 1970, approximately 2.39:1) is often incorrectly described (rounded) as 2.40:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] After 1952, a number of aspect ratios were experimented with for anamorphic productions, including 2.66:1 and 2.55:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] A SMPTE specification for anamorphic projection from 1957 (PH22.106-1957) finally standardized the aperture to 2.35:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] An update in 1970 (PH22.106-1971) changed the aspect ratio to 2.39:1 in order to make splices less noticeable.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This aspect ratio of 2.39:1 was confirmed by the most recent revision from August 1993 (SMPTE 195–1993).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In American theaters, the common projection ratios are 1.85:1 and 2.39:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Some European countries have the repeating decimal 1.6:1 as the widescreen standard.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The "Academy ratio" of 1.375:1 was used for all cinema films in the sound era until 1953 (with the release of George Stevens's *Shane* in 1.6:1).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] During that time, television, which had a similar aspect ratio of 1.3:1, became a perceived threat to movie studios.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Hollywood responded by creating a large number of widescreen formats: CinemaScope (up to 2.6:1), Todd-AO (2.20:1), and VistaVision (up to 2.00:1) to name just a few.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The flat 1.85:1 aspect ratio debuted in May 1953, and became one of the most common cinema projection standards in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The goal of these various lenses and aspect ratios was to capture as much of the frame as possible, onto as large an area of the film as possible, in order to fully utilize the film being used.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Some of the aspect ratios were chosen to utilize smaller film sizes in order to save film costs while other aspect ratios were chosen to use larger film sizes in order to produce a wider higher resolution image.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In either case the image was squeezed horizontally to fit the film's frame size and avoid any unused film area.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The development of various film camera systems must ultimately cater to the placement of the frame in relation to the lateral constraints of the perforations and the optical soundtrack area.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] One clever wide screen alternative, VistaVision, used standard 35 mm film running sideways through the camera gate, so that the sprocket holes were above and below frame, allowing a larger horizontal negative size per frame as only the vertical size was now restricted by the perforations.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] There were even a limited number of projectors constructed to also run the print-film horizontally.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Generally, however, the 1.50:1 ratio of the initial VistaVision image was optically converted to a vertical print (on standard four-perforation 35 mm movie film) to show with the standard projectors available at theaters, and was then masked in the projector to the United States standard of 1.85:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The format was briefly revived by Lucasfilm in the late 1970s for visual effects work that required a larger negative size (due to image degradation from the optical printing steps necessary to make multi-layer composites).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It went into obsolescence largely due to better cameras, lenses, and film stocks available for standard four-perforation formats, in addition to increased lab costs for making prints in comparison to more standard vertical processes.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Super 16 mm film was frequently used for television production due to its lower cost, lack of need for soundtrack space on the film itself (as it is not projected but rather transferred to video), and aspect ratio similar to 16:9 (the native ratio of Super 16 mm is 15:9).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It also can be blown up to 35 mm for theatrical release and therefore is sometimes used for feature films.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Square displays are rarely used in devices and monitors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Nonetheless, video consumption on social apps has grown rapidly and led to the emergence of new video formats more suited to mobile devices that can be held in horizontal and vertical orientations.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In that sense, square video was popularized by mobile apps such as Instagram and Vine and has since been supported by other major social platforms including Facebook and X.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It can fill nearly twice as much screen space compared to 16:9 format (when the device is held differently while viewing from how video was recorded).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 4:3 (1.3:1) (generally read as Four-Three, Four-by-Three, or Four-to-Three) for standard television for fullscreen aspect ratio 1.3:1 has been in use since the invention of moving picture cameras, and many computer monitors used to employ the same aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 4:3 was the aspect ratio used for 35 mm films in the silent era.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is also very close to the 1.375:1 Academy ratio, defined by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences as a standard after the advent of optical sound-on-film.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] By having TV match this aspect ratio, movies originally photographed on 35 mm film could be satisfactorily viewed on TV in the early days of the medium (i.e. the 1940s and the 1950s).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] With the adoption of high-definition television, the majority of modern televisions are now produced with 16:9 displays instead.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 14:9 (generally named as Fourteen-by-Nine, Fourteen-Nine, and Fourteen-to-Nine) is the aspect ratio mainly used when the 4:3 programs are cropped.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 16:10 (8:5) is an aspect ratio mostly used for computer displays and tablet computers.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The width of the display is 1.6 times its height.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This ratio is close to the golden ratio " $\varphi$ " which is approximately 1.618.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] LCD computer displays using the 16:10 ratio started to appear in the mass market from 2003.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] By 2008, 16:10 had become the most common aspect ratio for LCD monitors and laptop displays.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Since 2010, however, 16:9 has become the mainstream standard, driven by the 1080p standard for high definition television and lower manufacturing costs.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] At the time, 16:10 also had 90% of the notebook market and was the most commonly used aspect ratio for laptops.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] However, 16:10 had a short reign as the most common aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Around 2009–2010, there was a rapid shift by computer display manufacturers to the 16:9 aspect ratio and by 2011 16:10 had almost disappeared from new mass market products.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] According to Net Applications, by October 2012 the market share of 16:10 displays had dropped to less than 23 percent.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Notably, Apple used 16:10 for all of its MacBook models until 2021, when the 5th-generation MacBook Pro switched to a taller aspect ratio of approximately 1.54:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The MacBook Air switched to the same aspect ratio with its 5th generation in 2022.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Both aspect ratios are designed to maintain the 16:10 ratio for standard content, with extra area at the top of the display to house the front camera notch and the macOS menu bar.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 16:9 (1.78:1) (generally named as Sixteen-by-Nine, Sixteen-Nine, and Sixteen-to-Nine) is the international standard format of HDTV, non-HD digital television and analog widescreen television PALplus.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Japan's Hi-Vision originally started with a 5:3 (= 15:9) ratio but converted when the international standards group introduced a wider ratio of 5+1⁄3 to 3 (= 16:9).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Many digital video cameras have the capability to record in 16:9 (= 42:32), and 16:9 is the only widescreen aspect ratio natively supported by the DVD standard.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] DVD producers can also choose to show even wider ratios such as 1.66:1, 1.75:1, 1.77:1 and 1.78:1 within the 16:9 DVD frame by hard matting or adding black bars within the image itself.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The 16:9 aspect ratio was used often in British TVs in the United Kingdom in the 1990s, and is also used in smartphones, laptops, and desktops.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] When theater attendance dropped, Hollywood created widescreen aspect ratios in order to differentiate the film industry from TV, with one of the most common being the 1.85:1 ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The 2.00:1 aspect ratio was first used in the 1950s for the RKO Superscope format.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Since 1998, cinematographer Vittorio Storaro has advocated for a format named "Univisium" that uses a 2.00:1 format.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Univisium has gained little traction in the theatrical film market, but has recently been used by Netflix and Amazon Video for productions such as *House of Cards* and *Transparent*, respectively.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This aspect ratio is similar to the 1.90:1 standard acquisition formats mandated by these content platforms and is not necessarily a creative choice.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The Apple iPhone X also has a similar screen ratio of 19.5:9 (2.16:1).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Anamorphic format is the cinematography technique of shooting a widescreen picture on standard 35 mm film or other visual recording media with a non-widescreen native aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] When projected the image is then stretched back into the original proportions.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Often, screen specifications are given by their diagonal length.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The following formulae can be used to find the height (*h*), width (*w*) and area (*A*), where *r* stands for ratio, written as a fraction of *x* by *y*, and *d* for diagonal length.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This article primarily addresses the aspect ratio of images *as displayed,* which is more formally referred to as the **display aspect ratio (DAR)**.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In digital images, there is a distinction with the **storage aspect ratio (SAR)**, which is the ratio of numbers of pixels.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] If an image is displayed with square pixels, then these ratios agree.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] If, instead, non-square ("rectangular") pixels are used, then these ratios differ.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] However, because standard definition digital video was originally based on digitally sampling analog television, the 720 horizontal pixels actually capture a slightly wider image to avoid loss of the original analog picture.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In actual images, these extra pixels are often partly or entirely black, as only the center 704 horizontal pixels carry actual 4:3 or 16:9 image.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Hence, the actual pixel aspect ratio PAR for PAL video is a little different from that given by the formula, specifically 12:11 for PAL and 10:11 for NTSC.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For consistency, the same effective pixel aspect ratios are used even for standard definition digital video originated in digital form rather than converted from analog.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For more details refer to the main article.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In analog images such as film there is no notion of pixel, nor notion of SAR or PAR, and "aspect ratio" refers unambiguously to DAR.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Actual displays do not generally have non-square pixels, though digital sensors might; they are rather a mathematical abstraction used in resampling images to convert between resolutions.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Today they arise particularly in transcoding between resolutions with different SARs.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] DAR is also known as *image aspect ratio* and *picture aspect ratio*, though the latter can be confused with *pixel* aspect ratio; PAR is also known as *sample aspect ratio*, though it can also be confused with *storage* aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 's 30-line mechanical television in the early 1930s.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] ratio, this ratio was used briefly during the transitional period when the film industry was converting to sound, from 1926 to 1932 approx.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is produced by superimposing an optical soundtrack over a full-gate 1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] aperture in printing, resulting in an almost square image.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Films shot in this ratio are often projected or transferred to video incorrectly using a 1.375:1 mask or squashed to 1.375:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Notably one of the few popular display aspect ratios narrower than 4:3, and one popularised by business (CAD, DTP) rather than entertainment use, as it is well-suited to full-page layout editing.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Historically, 5:4 was also the original aspect ratio of early 405-line television broadcasts, which progressed to a wider 4:3 as the idea of broadcasting cinema films gained traction.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This format is still used in many personal video cameras today and has influenced the selection or design of other aspect ratios.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 35 mm full-screen sound film image, nearly universal in films between 1932 and 1953.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Rarely used in theatrical context nowadays, but occasionally used in other contexts.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] IMAX productions use 70 mm wide film (the same as used for 70 mm feature films), but the film runs through the camera and projector horizontally.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] This allows for a physically larger area for each image.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The aspect ratio of 35 mm film used for still photography when eight perforations are exposed.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Widescreen aspect ratio sometimes used in shooting commercials etc. as a compromise format between 4:3 and 16:9.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 's SD feed until January 2016 was presented in this ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Widescreen computer monitor ratio (for instance, 1920×1200 resolution).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] , later a standard among several European countries.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is also the native Super 16 mm frame ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Sometimes this ratio is rounded to 1.67:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] :1 ratio (a compromise between the 1.85:1 theatrical ratio and the 1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] produced elements of some post-1950s theatrical films in a 1.33:1 ratio for television broadcast versions, and later matted or cropped to a 1.75:1 widescreen aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] was rereleased in 1973 in the 1.75:1 aspect ratio, not its original 1.37:1 Academy ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Also used increasingly in personal video cameras.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Sometimes this ratio is rounded to 1.78:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 35 mm American and British widescreen standard for theatrical film.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] computers in the 1990s, with the resolution being specified as 1920×1024.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] digital cinema basic resolution container aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Used as a flat ratio for some American studios in the 1950s and abandoned in the 1960s.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] but often referred to as 2.35:1 anyway, due to old convention.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] films released after 1972 are shot in this standard for theatrical exhibition.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] But this aspect ratio is still seen on some higher-end monitors, which are sometimes called UltraWide monitors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] theatrical viewings, commercials, and some music videos.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Rounded notation of 2.39:1 also known as 2.40:1.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] All film releases may use 800 lines of the 1920×800 resolution resulting in the 2.40:1 aspect ratio of Blu-ray Disc.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] at full height (three specially captured 35 mm images projected side by side into one composite widescreen image).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] output from Super 16 mm negative when an anamorphic lens system has been used.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Effectively, an image that is of the ratio 24:9 is squashed onto the native 15:9 aspect ratio of a Super 16 mm negative.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] before optical sound was added to the film in 1954.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In 2017, Samsung and Philips announced "Super UltraWide displays", with aspect ratio of 32:9.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Ultra-WideScreen 3.6 video format didn't spread, as cinemas in an even wider ScreenX 270° format were released.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Uses nine 4:3 35 mm projectors to show an image that surrounds the viewer.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Used in subsequent Disney theme parks and other past applications.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Multiple aspect ratios create additional burdens on directors and the public, and confusion among TV broadcasters.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is common for a widescreen film to be presented in an altered format (cropped, letterboxed or expanded beyond the original aspect ratio).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is also not uncommon for windowboxing to occur (when letterbox and pillarbox happen simultaneously).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For instance, a 16:9 broadcast could embed a 4:3 commercial within the 16:9 image area.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] A viewer watching on a standard 4:3 (non-widescreen) television would see a 4:3 image of the commercial with 2 sets of black stripes, vertical and horizontal (windowboxing or the postage stamp effect).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] A similar scenario may also occur for a widescreen set owner when viewing 16:9 material embedded in a 4:3 frame, and then watching that in 16:9.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Active Format Description is a mechanism used in digital broadcasting to avoid this problem.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] It is also common that a 4:3 image is stretched horizontally to fit a 16:9 screen to avoid pillarboxing but distorts the image so subjects appear short and fat.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Both NTSC and PAL have provisions for some data pulses contained within the video signal used to signal the aspect ratio (See ITU-R BT.1119-1 – Widescreen signaling for broadcasting).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] These pulses are detected by television sets that have widescreen displays and cause the television to automatically switch to 16:9 display mode.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] When 4:3 material is included (such as the aforementioned commercial), the television switches to a 4:3 display mode to correctly display the material.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Where a video signal is transmitted via a European SCART connection, one of the status lines is used to signal 16:9 material as well.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Many digital still cameras offer user options for selecting multiple image aspect ratios.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Some achieve this through the use of multi-aspect sensors (notably Panasonic), while others simply crop their native image format to have the output match the desired image aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 1:1 is the classic Kodak image, and is available as a choice in some digital still cameras, and hearkens back to the days of film cameras when the square image was popular with photographers using twin lens reflex cameras.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] These medium format cameras used 120 film rolled onto spools.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The 6 × 6 cm image size was the classic 1:1 format in the recent past.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 120 film can still be found and used today.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Many Polaroid instant films were designed as square formats.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Furthermore, up until August 2015, photo-sharing site Instagram only allowed users to upload images in 1:1 format.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In 2017, Fujifilm added the 1:1 Instax Square format to their lineup of instant film cameras with the SQ10, followed by the fully analogue SQ6 in 2018.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Common in large and medium format photography (with "6 × 7" cameras that have an actual size of 56 mm × 70 mm [2.2 in × 2.8 in]), which fits the common print paper size of 8 in × 10 in (20.3 cm × 25.4 cm) without cropping and is still in common use for prints from digital cameras.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 4:3 is used by most digital point-and-shoot cameras, Four Thirds system, Micro Four Thirds system cameras and medium format 645 cameras.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The 4:3 digital format popularity was developed to match the then prevailing digital displays of the time, 4:3 computer monitors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The next several formats have their roots in classic film photography image sizes, both the classic 35 mm film camera, and the multiple format Advanced Photo System (APS) film camera.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The APS camera was capable of selecting any of three image formats, APS-H ("High Definition" mode), APS-C ("Classic" mode) and APS-P ("Panoramic" mode).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 3:2 is used by classic 35 mm film cameras using a 36 mm × 24 mm image size, and their digital derivatives represented by DSLRs.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Typical DSLRs come in two flavors, the so-called professional "full frame" (36 mm × 24 mm) sensors and variations of smaller, so-called "APS-C" sensors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The term "APS" is derived from another film format known as APS and the "-C" refers to "Classic" mode, which exposed images over a smaller area (25.1 mm × 16.7 mm) but retaining the same "classic" 3:2 proportions as full frame 35 mm film cameras.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] When discussing DSLRs and their non-SLR derivatives, the term APS-C has become an almost generic term.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The major camera manufacturers, including Canon, Sony, and Nikon, each developed and established sensor standards for their own versions of APS-C-sized and proportioned sensors.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Canon actually developed two standards, APS-C and a slightly larger area APS-H (not to be confused with the APS-H film format), while Nikon developed its own APS-C standard, which it calls DX.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Regardless of the different flavors of sensors, and their varying sizes, they are close enough to the original APS-C image size, and maintain the classic 3:2 image proportions that these sensors are generally known as an "APS-C" sized sensor.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Widescreen computer monitors did not become popular until the advent of HDTV, which uses a 16:9 image aspect ratio.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Known as APS-H (30.2 mm × 16.7 mm), with the "-H" denoting "High Definition", the 16:9 format is also the standard image aspect ratio for HDTV.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 16:9 is gaining popularity as a format in all classes of consumer still cameras which also shoot High Definition (HD) video.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] When still cameras have an HD video capability, some can also record stills in the 16:9 format, ideal for display on HD televisions and widescreen computer displays.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] 3:1 is yet another format that can find its roots in the APS film camera.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Known as APS-P (30.2 × 9.5 mm), with the -P" denoting "Panorama", the 3:1 format was used for panorama photography.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] The APS-P panorama standard is the least adhered to any APS standard, and panoramic implementation varies with by manufacturer on different cameras, with the only commonality being that the image is much longer than it is tall, in the classic "panorama" style.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Common print sizes in the United States (in inches) include 4×6 (1.5), 5×7 (1.4), 4×5 and 8×10 (1.25), and 11×14 (1.27); large format cameras typically use one of these aspect ratios.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Medium-format cameras typically have format designated by nominal sizes in centimeters (6×6, 6×7, 6×9, 6×4.5), but these numbers should not be interpreted as exact in computing aspect ratios.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For example, the usable height of 120-format roll film is 56mm, so a width of 70mm (as in 6×7) yields an aspect ratio of 4:5 – ideal for enlarging to make an 8×10" portrait.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] Print sizes are usually defined by their portrait dimensions (tall) while equipment aspect ratios are defined by their landscape dimensions (wide, flipped sideways).
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] A good example of this a 4×6 print (6 inch wide by 4 inch tall landscape) perfectly matches the 3:2 aspect ratio of a DSLR/35 mm, since 6/2=3 and 4/2=2.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For analog projection of photographic slides, projector and screen use a 1:1 aspect ratio, supporting horizontal and vertical orientation equally well.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] In contrast, digital projection technology typically supports vertically oriented images only at a fraction of the resolution of landscape-oriented images.
[src:floorplanning/aspect-ratio-image] For example, projecting a digital still image having a 3:2 aspect ratio on a 16:9 projector employs 84.3% of available resolution in horizontal orientation, but only 37.5% in vertical orientation.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] In electronic design automation, a **floorplan** of an integrated circuit consists of a schematic arrangement of its major functional blocks on the chip area and the specification of high-level parameters such as the **aspect ratio** or **core utilization**.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] The design step in which floorplans are created is called **floorplanning**, an early stage in the design flow for integrated circuit design.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] Various mathematical abstractions of this problem have been studied.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] The floorplanning design stage consists of various steps with the aim of finding floorplans that allow a timing-clean routing and spread power consumption over the whole chip.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] In mathematics floorplanning refers to the problem of packing smaller rectangles with a fixed or unfixed orientation into a larger rectangle.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] The dimensions of the larger and smaller rectangles might be fixed (hard constraints) or must be optimized (soft constraints).
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] Additionally, a measure modelling the quality of routing that the floorplan allows might be optimized.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] Various variants of rectangle packing are NP-hard.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] A sliceable floorplan is a floorplan that may be defined recursively as described below.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] The process is known as guillotine cutting.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] Sliceable floorplans have been used in a number of early electronic design automation tools for a number of reasons.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] Sliceable floorplans may be conveniently represented by binary trees (more specifically, *k*-d trees), which correspond to the order of slicing.
[src:floorplanning/floorplan-microelectronics] More importantly, a number of NP-hard problems with floorplans have polynomial time algorithms when restricted to sliceable floorplans.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] Originally the overall process was called tapeout, as historically early ICs used graphical black crepe tape on mylar media for photo imaging (erroneously believed to reference magnetic data—the photo process greatly predated magnetic media).
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] When using a standard process—where the interaction of the many chemical, thermal, and photographic variables is known and carefully controlled—the behaviour of the final integrated circuit depends largely on the positions and interconnections of the geometric shapes.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] Using a computer-aided layout tool, the layout engineer—or layout technician—places and connects all of the components that make up the chip such that they meet certain criteria—typically: performance, size, density, and manufacturability.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] This practice is often subdivided between two primary layout disciplines: analog and digital.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] The generated layout must pass a series of checks in a process known as physical verification.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] When all verification is complete, layout post processing is applied where the data is also translated into an industry-standard format, typically GDSII, and sent to a semiconductor foundry.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] The milestone completion of the layout process of sending this data to the foundry is now colloquially called "tapeout".
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] The foundry converts the data into mask data and uses it to generate the photomasks used in a photolithographic process of semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] In the earlier, simpler, days of IC design, layout was done by hand using opaque tapes and films, an evolution derived from early days of printed circuit board (PCB) design -- tape-out.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] Modern IC layout is done with the aid of IC layout editor software, mostly automatically using EDA tools, including place and route tools or schematic-driven layout tools.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] Typically this involves a library of standard cells.
[src:floorplanning/integrated-circuit-layout] The manual operation of choosing and positioning the geometric shapes is informally known as "polygon pushing".
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] In integrated circuit design, **physical design** is a step in the standard design cycle which follows after the circuit design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] At this step, circuit representations of the components (devices and interconnects) of the design are converted into geometric representations of shapes which, when manufactured in the corresponding layers of materials, will ensure the required functioning of the components.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This geometric representation is called an integrated circuit layout.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This step is usually split into several sub-steps, which include both design and verification and validation of the layout.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Modern day Integrated Circuit (IC) design is split up into *Front-end Design using HDLs* and *Back-end Design* or *Physical Design*.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The inputs to physical design are (i) a netlist, (ii) library information on the basic devices in the design, and (iii) a technology file containing the manufacturing constraints.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Physical design is usually concluded by *Layout Post Processing*, in which amendments and additions to the chip layout are performed.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This is followed by the wafer fabrication, the manufacturing process whereby designs are transferred via photomasks onto silicon dies which are then packaged into ICs.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Each of the phases mentioned above has design flows associated with them.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] These design flows lay down the process and guide-lines/framework for that phase.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The physical design flow uses the technology libraries that are provided by the fabrication houses.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] These technology files provide information regarding the type of silicon wafer used, the standard cells used, the layout rules (like DRC in VLSI), etc.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The physical design engineer (sometimes called physical engineer or physical designer) is responsible for the design and layout (routing), specifically in ASIC/FPGA design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Typically, the IC physical design is categorized into full custom, semi-custom, gate array, and FPGA design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The design flow used depends strongly on the requirements.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Full custom design is the slowest and most expensive, but offers potentially the highest performance.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Semi-custom or ASIC is somewhat easier as the components have been pre-characterized, although in some cases the designer has the flexibility to design/modify design blocks from vendor provided libraries in ASIC.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This flexibility is missing for flows using FPGAs (e.g.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Altera or Xilinx), which are the easiest to implement, as the chips are already fabricated.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] These offer the advantage of no fabrication time (a chip designed today can be running tomorrow) and by far the easiest debugging, but have the lowest performance and the highest cost per gate.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] There are detailed PD flows that are used depending on the tools used and the methodology/technology.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The ASIC physical design flow uses the technology libraries that are provided by the fabrication houses.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Technologies are commonly classified according to minimal feature size.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Standard sizes, in the order of miniaturization, are *2μm, 1μm, 0.5μm, 0.35μm, 0.25μm, 180nm, 130nm, 90nm, 65nm, 45nm, 28nm, 22nm, 18nm, 14nm, etc.* They may be also classified according to major manufacturing approaches: n-Well process, twin-well process, SOI process, etc.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Physical design is based on a netlist which is the end result of the logic synthesis process.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Synthesis converts the RTL design, usually coded in VHDL or Verilog HDL, to gate-level descriptions which the next set of tools can read and understand.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This netlist contains information on the cells used, their interconnections, area used, and other details.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] During the synthesis process, constraints are applied to ensure that the design meets the specified functionality and speed.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Only after the netlist is verified for functionality and timing it is sent for the physical design flow.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Note however that timing at this point is only an estimate, as the parasitics from the physical design are not yet known.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Partitioning is a process of dividing the chip into small blocks.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This is done mainly to separate different functional blocks and also to make placement and routing easier.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Partitioning can be done in the RTL design phase when the design engineer partitions the entire design into sub-blocks and then proceeds to design each module.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] These modules are linked together in the main module called the TOP LEVEL module.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This kind of partitioning is commonly referred to as Logical Partitioning.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The goal of partitioning is to split the circuit such that the number of connections between partitions is minimized.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The second step in the physical design flow is *floorplanning*.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Based on the area of the design and the hierarchy, a suitable floorplan is decided upon.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Floorplanning takes into account the macros used in the design, memory, other IP cores and their placement needs, the routing possibilities, and also the area of the entire design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Floorplanning also determines the IO structure and aspect ratio of the design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] A bad floorplan will lead to wastage of die area and routing congestion.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] In many design methodologies, *area* and *speed* are the subjects of trade-offs.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This is due to limited routing resources, as the more resources used, the slower the operation.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Optimizing for minimum area allows the design both to use fewer resources, and for greater proximity of the sections of the design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] This leads to shorter interconnect distances, fewer routing resources used, faster end-to-end signal paths, and even faster and more consistent place and route times.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Done correctly, there are no negatives to floorplanning.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] As a general rule, data-path sections benefit most from floorplanning, whereas random logic, state machines, and other non-structured logic can safely be left to the placer section of the place and route software.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Data paths are typically the areas of the design where multiple bits are processed in parallel with each bit being modified the same way with maybe some influence from adjacent bits.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Example structures that make up data paths are Adders, Subtractors, Counters, Registers, and Muxes.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Earlier stages, when the placement is unknown, generally use a simple Wire Load Model (WLM), often an estimate based on fanout.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Placement uses more accurate RC values, typically estimated from the bounding box of all pins of a net, but without detailed routing.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The goal of **clock tree synthesis** (**CTS**) is to insure proper operation of a clocked circuit, primarily by minimizing skew while controlling insertion delay.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] The clock is a single logical signal of high fanout before CTS, as shown in the picture.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] After CTS setup times should be met, and hold slack should be improved.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] A clock tree begins at a source (normally defined in an .sdc file) and ends at the clock pins of flip-flops.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] There are two types of stop pins known as *ignore* pins and *sync* pins.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] 'Don't touch' circuits and pins in front end (logic synthesis) are treated as 'ignore' circuits or pins at back end (physical synthesis).
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] 'Ignore' pins are ignored for timing analysis.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] If the clock is divided into multiple phases then a separate skew analysis is necessary.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Rigidity is the term coined in Astro to indicate the relaxation of constraints.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Higher the rigidity means tighter constraints.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] In **clock tree optimization** (CTO) clock can be shielded so that noise is not coupled to other signals.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] But shielding increases area by 12 to 15%.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Since the clock signal is global in nature the same metal layer used for power routing is used for clock also.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] CTO is achieved by buffer sizing, gate sizing, buffer relocation, level adjustment and HFN synthesis.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] We try to improve setup slack in pre-placement, in placement and post placement optimization before CTS stages while neglecting hold slack.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] In post placement optimization after CTS hold slack is improved.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] As a result of CTS lot of buffers are added.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Generally for 100k gates around 650 buffers are added.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] There are two types of routing in the physical design process, global routing and detailed routing.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Global routing allocates routing resources that are used for connections.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] It also does track assignment for a particular net.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Detailed routing does the actual connections.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Different constraints that are to be taken care during the routing are DRC, wire length, timing etc.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Physical verification checks the correctness of the generated layout design.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] Layout Post Processing, also known mask data preparation, often concludes physical design and verification.
[src:floorplanning/physical-design-electronics] It converts the physical layout (polygons) into mask data (instructions for the photomask writer).
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] A placer takes a given synthesized circuit netlist together with a technology library and produces a valid placement layout.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] The layout is optimized according to the aforementioned objectives and ready for cell resizing and buffering — a step essential for timing and signal integrity satisfaction.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Clock tree synthesis and Routing follow, completing the physical design process.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In many cases, parts of, or the entire, physical design flow are iterated a number of times until design closure is achieved.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In the case of application-specific integrated circuits, or ASICs, the chip's core layout area comprises a number of fixed height rows, with either some or no space between them.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Each row consists of a number of sites which can be occupied by the circuit components.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] A free site is a site that is not occupied by any component.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Circuit components are either standard cells, macro blocks, or I/O pads.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Standard cells have a fixed height equal to a row's height, but have variable widths.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] The width of a cell is an integral number of sites.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] On the other hand, blocks are typically larger than cells and have variable heights that can stretch a multiple number of rows.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Some blocks can have preassigned locations — say from a previous floorplanning process — which limit the placer's task to assigning locations for just the cells.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In this case, the blocks are typically referred to by fixed blocks.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Alternatively, some or all of the blocks may not have preassigned locations.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In this case, they have to be placed with the cells in what is commonly referred to as mixed-mode placement.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In addition to ASICs, placement retains its prime importance in gate array structures such as field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Here, prefabricated transistors are typically arranged in rows (or “arrays”) that are separated by routing channels.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement maps the circuit's subcircuits into programmable FPGA logic blocks in a manner that guarantees the completion of the subsequent stage of routing.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement is formulated as **constrained optimization**.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In particular, the clock cycle of a chip is determined by the delay of its longest path, usually referred to as the critical path.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Given a performance specification, a placer must ensure that no path exists with delay exceeding the maximum specified delay.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Additionally, it is desirable to finish the placement process quickly.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Total wirelength is typically the primary objective of most existing placers and serves as a precursor to other optimizations because, e.g., power and delay tend to grow with wire length.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Total wire length determines the routing demand and whether it can be satisfied by the routing supply defined by available routing tracks.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] However, making wires very short sometimes leads to local routing demand exceeding local routing supply.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Such situations often require routing detours, which increase wire lengths and signal delays.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Therefore, after preliminary optimization of total wirelength, it is also important to handle routing congestion.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Power minimization typically notes wires with greater switching activity factors and assigns greater priority to making them shorter.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] When many "hot" components are placed nearby, a hot spot may arise and lead to harmful temperature gradients.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In such cases, components can be spread out.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement is divided into global placement and detailed placement.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Global placement introduces dramatic changes by distributing all the instances to appropriate locations in a global scale with minor overlaps allowed.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Detailed placement shifts each instance to nearby legal location with very moderate layout change.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement and overall design quality is most dependent on the global placement performance.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Early techniques for placement of integrated circuits can be categorized as combinatorial optimization.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] For IC designs with thousands or tens of thousands of components, **simulated annealing** methodologies such as TimberWolf exhibits the best results.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] When IC designs grew to millions of components, placement leveraged **hypergraph partitioning** using nested-partitioning frameworks such as Capo.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Combinatorial methods directly prevent component overlaps but struggle with interconnect optimization at large scale.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] They are typically stochastic and can produce very different results for the same input when launched multiple times.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Analytical methods for global placement model interconnect length by a continuous function and minimize this function directly subject to component density constraints.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] These methods run faster and scale better than combinatorial methods, but do not prevent component overlaps and must be postprocessed by combinatorial methods for detailed placement.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] **Quadratic placement** is an early analytical method that models interconnect length by a quadratic function and uses high-performance quadratic optimization techniques.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] When it was developed, it demonstrated competitive quality of results and also stability, unlike combinatorial methods.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] GORDIAN formulates the wirelength cost as a quadratic function while still spreading cells apart through recursive partitioning.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] The algorithm models placement density as a linear term into the quadratic cost function and solves the placement problem by pure quadratic programming.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] A common enhancement is weighting each net by the inverse of its length on the previous iteration.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] Provided the process converges, this minimizes an objective **linear** in the wirelength.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] The majority of modern quadratic placers (KraftWerk, FastPlace, SimPL) follow this framework, each with different heuristics on how to determine the linear density force.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] ePlace is a state-of-the-art global placement algorithm.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] It spreads instances apart by simulating an electrostatic field, which minimizes quality overhead thus achieves good performance.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] In 2021, Google Brain reported good results from the use of AI techniques (in particular, reinforcement learning) for the placement problem.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] However, this result is quite controversial, as the paper does not contain head-to-head comparisons to existing placers, and is difficult to replicate due to proprietary content.
[src:floorplanning/placement-electronic-design-automation] At least one initially favorable commentary has been retracted upon further review.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Before the introduction of VLSI technology, most ICs had a limited set of functions they could perform.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] An electronic circuit might consist of a CPU, ROM, RAM and other glue logic.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] VLSI enables IC designers to add all of these into one chip.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The history of the transistor dates to the 1920s when several inventors attempted devices that were intended to control current in solid-state diodes and convert them into triodes.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Success came after World War II, when the use of silicon and germanium crystals as radar detectors led to improvements in fabrication and theory.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Scientists who had worked on radar returned to solid-state device development.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] With the invention of the first transistor at Bell Labs in 1947, the field of electronics shifted from vacuum tubes to solid-state devices.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] With the small transistor at their hands, electrical engineers of the 1950s saw the possibilities of constructing far more advanced circuits.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] However, as the complexity of circuits grew, problems arose.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] One problem was the size of the circuit.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] A complex circuit like a computer was dependent on speed.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] If the components were large, the wires interconnecting them must be long.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The electric signals took time to go through the circuit, thus slowing the computer.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The invention of the integrated circuit by Jack Kilby and Robert Noyce solved this problem by making all the components and the chip out of the same block (monolith) of semiconductor material.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The circuits could be made smaller, and the manufacturing process could be automated.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] This led to the idea of integrating all components on a single-crystal silicon wafer, which led to small-scale integration (SSI) in the early 1960s, and then medium-scale integration (MSI) in the late 1960s.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] General Micro-electronics introduced the first commercial MOS integrated circuit in 1964.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] In the early 1970s, MOS integrated circuit technology allowed the integration of more than 10,000 transistors in a single chip.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] This paved the way for VLSI in the 1970s and 1980s, with tens of thousands of MOS transistors on a single chip (later hundreds of thousands, then millions, and now billions).
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The first semiconductor chips held two transistors each.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Subsequent advances added more transistors, and as a consequence, more individual functions or systems were integrated over time.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] The first integrated circuits held only a few devices, perhaps as many as ten diodes, transistors, resistors and capacitors, making it possible to fabricate one or more logic gates on a single device.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Now known retrospectively as *small-scale integration* (SSI), improvements in technique led to devices with hundreds of logic gates, known as *medium-scale integration* (MSI).
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Further improvements led to *large-scale integration* (LSI), i.e. systems with at least a thousand logic gates.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Current technology has moved far past this mark and today's microprocessors have many millions of gates and billions of individual transistors.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] At one time, there was an effort to name and calibrate various levels of large-scale integration above VLSI.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Terms like *ultra-large-scale integration* (ULSI) were used.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] But the huge number of gates and transistors available on common devices has rendered such fine distinctions moot.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Terms suggesting greater than VLSI levels of integration are no longer in widespread use.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] In 2008, billion-transistor processors became commercially available.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] This became more commonplace as semiconductor fabrication advanced from the then-current generation of 65 nanometer processors.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Current designs, unlike the earliest devices, use extensive electronic design automation and automated logic synthesis to lay out the transistors, enabling higher levels of complexity in the resulting logic functionality.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Certain high-performance logic blocks, like the SRAM (static random-access memory) cell, are still designed by hand to ensure the highest efficiency.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Structured VLSI design is a modular methodology originated by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway for saving microchip area by minimizing the interconnect fabric area.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] This is obtained by repetitive arrangement of rectangular macro blocks which can be interconnected using wiring by abutment.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] An example is partitioning the layout of an adder into a row of equal bit slice cells.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] In complex designs this structuring may be achieved by hierarchical nesting.
[src:floorplanning/very-large-scale-integration] Structured VLSI design had been popular in the early 1980s, but lost its popularity later because of the advent of placement and routing tools wasting a lot of area by routing, which is tolerated because of the progress of Moore's law.
